The United States presidential election of 2024, scheduled for Tuesday, November 5, 2020, will be the 60th quadrennial U.S. presidential election. Voters will select presidential electors who in turn will elect a new president and vice president through the electoral college.

The election has been the topic of speculation and analysis by commentators as it will be the first U.S. presidential election to occur after the redistribution of votes in the [[United States Electoral College]] occurring as a result of the [[2020 United States Census]]. In a study of potential redistribution of votes published in ''[[Perspectives on Politics]]'', [[University of Georgia]] political scientist Edward Burmila concluded that:<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burmila|first1=Edward|title=The Electoral College after Census 2010 and 2020: The Political Impact of Population Growth and Redistribution|journal=[[Perspectives on Politics]]|date=December 2009|volume=7|issue=4|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=6677188}}</ref>

{{cquote|Democratic presidential candidates will find it increasingly difficult to win elections without having some success in the South and Southwest as Barack Obama did in 2008 but many previous candidates failed to do. While migration will also benefit some solid Democratic states such as California, on balance Republican presidential candidates are poised to benefit from the status of Sun Belt states as magnets for both foreign immigration and domestic migration from a retirement cohort of unprecedented size.}}

